Quote:  The pith of the trunk and leaf bases of mamaku (<i>Cyathea medullaris</i>) were frequently eaten by Maori, especially when travelling, and the king fern or para (<i>Marattia salicina</i>) was cultivated for its tuberous root, which was condisered a great delicacy when roasted.
